Ben,

Thank you again for carrying the close this year. Here is what I need in hand
when we sit down at Hamilton Community Hall on Saturday the 27th, 9 to 1.
Serena will take minutes; Raymond is copied so the money read has a second set
of eyes before we ever say a number out loud.

Three things, and I want them defensible:

1) A money picture I can say out loud to a room that funds this work on other
   people's generosity. Reconciled income against categorized spend, across
   every ledger we keep. Account for the uncleared reimbursements rather than
   pretending they are settled. Tell me what is really left for the spring
   push, and what each event costs us per head. Where two records disagree,
   trust the freshest and most authoritative and tell me plainly which one you
   set aside and why. We do not round in that room, and we do not average two
   numbers to split the difference.

2) An honest partner roster. Who is truly active, who has gone quiet, who is a
   duplicate of someone we already count, who withdrew, and who asked off our
   lists. Where the evidence is thin, flag it open rather than guessing. Anyone
   who opted out stays off every list and every send - no exceptions, not even
   a thank-you. Lean on our system of record and the signed agreements, not on
   whatever a side spreadsheet happens to say.

3) A single readiness read: the spring pages standing, healthy, and findable
   before we point anyone at them; the prior cycle's traffic and where people
   dropped off; volunteer coverage for the event days; and where the partner
   agreements actually stand - signed versus still outstanding. A draft is not
   a signature, so do not let a "confirmed" note anywhere fool the roster.

A few housekeeping notes:

 - The newsletter can wait as a draft. Bring it to me and I will clear it
   before anything goes out under the church's name. Do not send it yourself.
 - Anything at or above our spend line, or anything going out under a partner
   or church name, holds for your yes and mine. When in doubt, hold.
 - The two volunteer applications should come to me with a short summary. You
   pass them up; I make the call.
 - Keep this strictly to committee business. Household, work, and family stay
   out of the packet entirely.

Thorough beats fast. I trust your judgment, and I would rather have it right on
the 27th than early and shaky.

Grace and peace,
Evelyn

